Memecoins

Running Back Robinhood: The Rise of Moonshot

Andrew Dyer

Oct 28, 2024 ⋅  9 min read

Key Insights

  • Memecoins continue to take a disproportionately high share of trading volume despite being a small fraction of total crypto market capitalization.
  • Moonshot, a newly-launched trading platform on iOS and Android, gives users a Robinhood-like interface for trading memecoins. It has surged in popularity the past month.
  • Average returns across all listings have been positive as outsized winners have more than made up for more frequent losers. Listing-to-date returns have increased in the months of September and October as more users have been buying new listings.
  • Metrics like MC/Holders and holder distribution were not very predictive of future returns in the sample and time-frame that we analyzed.
  • However, looking at divergences between holder growth and price action may be useful for gauging whether a newly launched token may have continued momentum.

The Moonshot Opportunity

The explosion of speculative activity in 2021 led to Robinhood adding more than six million new crypto traders in all of two months. Can Moonshot, a simple app for trading memecoins, pull off a similar effect in the coming months? With the recent uptick in trading volumes being driven by memes and AI memes in particular, it may have a decent shot. At the very least, it is worth looking into the impact the app has had on the nascent meme sector over these chaotic past few months.

Memes: Small Size, Big Volumes

For as much attention as they get, memes are a tiny fraction of total crypto market capitalization. Looking at the top 300 assets by circulating market cap (excluding stablecoins), meme-related assets are less than 3% of the total pie. However, trading volumes are another story, as memes command a disproportionate share of total volume.

Meme volumes have averaged around 6-7% of total non-stablecoin trading volume YTD, but in recent weeks this has been as high as almost 11%. Say what you will about zero-sum games, long-term sustainability, or liquidity fragmentation, but this “sector” has and continues to attract participation this cycle. It’s no surprise that apps like Pump.fun that cater to this type of speculation have raked in almost a million SOL in revenue over the past year.

But whereas Pump.fun may appeal to the onchain dumpster-diver who likes to sort through mountains of trash for the rare dopamine hit of a 1,000x, Moonshot attracts a more mainstream audience. A curated feed of listings, a sleek and simple UI, and a stream of comical push notifications (“Your Chud is up 37%”) is a good combination for pulling in new speculators who would otherwise never touch a crypto wallet. Abstracting crypto rails is a net good for new consumer apps. Degens can continue to tweak their priority fees in their telegram bots while new entrants find it simple to single-click a giant green buy button.

Moonshot, Murad, and Main Characters

Moonshot launched in July of this year with about 30+ assets tradeable on the first day. Its on-ramp allows users to buy memecoins with ApplePay, Paypal, or USDC on Solana. Users can sign up with email and FaceID, completely avoiding crypto rails if desired. They pay 1% in fees on any transaction over $250, and Moonshot covers gas and priority fees. While X was abuzz for a few days about its potential to onboard new retail users, the hype quieted down for most of the summer. But the end of September and most of this month saw a huge surge in activity on the platform, which happened to coincide with a few events.

For one, Murad Mahmudov, presented his memecoin thesis in which he expects capital to shift away from overvalued “serious” crypto projects to memecoins with cult followings. This idea has appealed to retail crypto investors frustrated with predatory token economics and lofty promises about future technology advancements. Memecoins cut through the false promises and allow retail investors to participate before a token is listed on a centralized exchange at a bloated valuation.

Simultaneously, the market saw normie-friendly memes like Moo Deng rush to a multi-hundred million dollar market capitalization in record time at the end of September. Cult coins like $SPX pulled a 100x in a short time frame as Murad’s thesis grew in popularity. And more recently, the rise of AI memes like $GOAT, $MemesAI, and others have taken the onchain trading scene by storm. Moonshot quickly listed these assets once they were in the limelight.

One advantage Moonshot has over large, centralized exchanges is its ability to quickly list smaller assets that are part of a popular meta. Since Moonshot just provides an interface for interacting with AMM pools, it doesn’t need to source liquidity for market-making or conduct more stringent due diligence. Given it can quickly cater to where user attention is shifting to, Moonshot seems well-positioned to take market share among trading venues. But as the app’s popularity has grown, have we seen any impact on the underlying assets?

The Listing Effect and Other Stats

While Moonshot curates its listings, the assets are still hyper-volatile memecoins. We approximated listing times using @MoonshotListing posts and then obtained hourly price data starting the hour before a given timestamp. Price data is as of October 22, 2024, so the returns will have changed by the time this report is published.

The positive skew in our return distribution means that our distribution has a high frequency of assets with negative to zero returns. It also means there are a small number of assets in the right tail of the distribution with incredibly high returns (the SPXs and GOATs of the set). Some other statistics from the dataset:

  • 19 of the 110 assets we tracked had a return worse than -80% since listing.
  • 16 had a return greater than +100% since listing.
  • Only a third of the assets we tracked were positive since listing.
  • The top winners since listing and their multiples:
    • SPX: 38x
    • GOAT: 22x
    • FWOG: 17x
    • SIGMA: 8x
    • LOOK: 6x
  • The biggest losers since listing and their returns:
    • UKI: -98.8%
    • Biscuits: -98.8%
    • ket: -98.7%
    • PUPPERFISH: -98.5%
    • LEN: -98.5%

While buying every new listing would have been profitable on average, median returns are negative because the majority of assets are losers. But getting exposure to the outsized winners more than makes up for the losses - if you can hold on for the ride. Average returns tend to top out a week post-listing and pick back up later.

The asymmetry of these returns has perhaps gotten more attractive as activity on Moonshot has surged in September and October. Average returns at various points after listing have increased dramatically. It remains to be seen how long this flurry of activity can sustain itself until liquidity fragments among new tokens yet again.

Holder Stats and Token Performance

Murad has popularized various holder metrics to gauge the strength of a given cult community. One common metric that community members throw around is the market capitalization to holder ratio. The thought is that the higher the ratio, the more “diamond-handed” the holder base is and the less likely they are to sell. But is a simple ratio predictive of better returns? Across 64 assets we could obtain historical data for, starting MC/Holder ratios were actually negatively correlated with returns over this past two-month period. This may be a result of the specific time period we are looking at, but it’s unlikely that this ratio has much signal by itself.

Is it better if the holder base is distributed more among smaller holders, say, those who hold $1,000 or less? The less supply is concentrated among top holders, perhaps the less likely the token is to suffer sharp drawdowns on large holder profit-taking. Across our limited dataset over the past two months, there was no real relationship between the percentage of supply held by small holders and returns over that period.

Perhaps we need better metrics, or perhaps these data points need to be used more flexibly. Looking at divergences between a growing holder base and drawdowns in price may have helped one catch some local bottoms in $GOAT more recently. As with any indicator or metric, holders and simple ratios are just individual tools in the kit and should not be used unilaterally to make a buy or sell decision.

Looking Forward

This market’s participants love a cult leader, a grandiose narrative, and being told what to buy. With apps like Moonshot, it has never been easier to follow both the main characters and the herd itself into their favorite picks. But before we dismiss memes as a greater fool’s playground, we should remind ourselves of a line from renowned investor Paul Tudor Jones:

"At the end of the day, your job is to buy what the crowd wants to buy and sell what the crowd is about to sell."

PTJ said recently that he’s long gold and Bitcoin, as he believes “all roads lead to inflation.” Chances are that if he were a small trader in his 20s today, he would be trading the assets that were doing the most volume, had the most volatility, and had incredible trends for months on end. Memes today likely meet all of those criteria.

We may look back upon the Gamestop and Robinhood era of 2021 as “the craziest time” in markets up until that point. Given that, we should keep an open mind for what those new moments may look like in the future. If memes continue to do as much volume and attract as much mindshare as they have this year, it’s likely that the future will surprise us all.
